Featured developer product
 
Adobe Launch
 
 
 
 
The Launch team recently did a showcase on the Adobe I/O blog about how they’re opening up APIs to allow developers to build their own integrations.
💭 Oh cool, I like open APIs! I didn’t know Adobe did that.

For the uninitiated, Launch is Adobe’s next-gen Dynamic Tag Management (DTM) solution, part of our Experience Cloud offering, which allows developers to collect custom data about their users and aggregate it across various digital marketing tools.

In the true spirit of open development, Launch gives our partners the ability to integrate with other marketing tools through their extensibility platform, and maintains a catalog of open source libraries to help accelerate these integrations.

tl;dr
  • Launch team's GitHub repo
  • External partner extension GitHub repo
  • Open Source dependencies
  • npm packages

Watch the product video

Henry Zhu
 
 
Henry Zhu works on Adobe's Behance team and contributes to a number of opens source projects. Most notably, Henry is a core team member of Babel, a popular JavaScript compiler used extensively throughout Adobe and by companies like Facebook, Google, and Netflix.

GitHub Insights
 
 
Todd O’Connor presented GitHub Insights at the Adobe Open Source Summit last month. This tool will help you visualize contributors to your organization, optimize your git and API calls, determine if you should be running fetch instead of clone operations, and much more.

This project is based on the open source Hubble project. Todd and the SCM team have already begun to get involved with discussions in Hubble — great to see Adobians contributing back to the OS community!
 
 
 
 
 
 
Contribute to this newsletter
 
 
The CHANGELOG newsletter works like an open source project. In fact, it even has a Gitcorp repo!

Content for a newsletter release can be submitted by anyone. All you have to do is create a new Gitcorp issue that includes the article's link. You can think of this as sending a pull request to an open source project.

Anyone can upvote interesting suggestions (and downvote the other ones). Voting on an article is simply done by adding a 👍 or 👎 reaction to the Github issue. This is similar to how you would upvote a pull request that adds a great feature to an open source project.

Newsletter releases will include the top voted articles. This ensures the most interesting content is shared with all developers across the company.
💭 Oh it's like merging a pull request and cutting a release for everyone to enjoy.
